  "opinion": "As a school teacher in Philadelphia who's watched generations of students navigate the educational system, I've seen how stereotype threat plays out in STEM classrooms. It's not just about the fear of confirming negative stereotypes—it's the quiet anxiety that makes students second-guess their own abilities when they're already struggling with complex concepts. For example, I remember a student who, after being told 'you're not cut out for math,' started skipping homework because she felt her intelligence was being questioned. This phenomenon isn't limited to girls; boys from underrepresented backgrounds often experience it too, especially when they're reminded of societal expectations about 'being good at STEM.' The problem is systemic—it starts with how we frame problems in class and how we respond to students who don't fit the 'typical' profile. We should address it head-on by creating environments where every student feels safe to make mistakes without judgment. That means reframing assessments to value process over perfection, celebrating diverse problem-solving styles, and explicitly challenging stereotypes in the curriculum. As someone who's anxious about my own performance in school, I know how much comfort comes from a teacher who sees you as a person, not just a statistic. In Philadelphia, where we have such a diverse student population, this work is critical to ensuring no child is held back by what they're told they can't do.",
